{
  "texts": [
    "For now, it might be helpful to reemphasise a key difference between her approach and the standard story.",
    "Anscombe, unlike Davidson, is explicitly committed to giving an account of action from within the perspective of ordinary practically rational agents who are able to make the kind of intuitive judgment on which the deviant causal chain problem hangs.",
    "Had we not this attunement to action's teleological microstructure, we could not appreciate what was wrong in deviant cases.",
    "But since we have it, on this view, we can pick out these cases and exclude them from our characterisation of intentional agency.",
    "17 That is, they can be ascribed to an individual agent if such an agent is conceived of as Anscombe suggests: as inhabiting an enabling context of things apt to be animated by her activity."
  ]
}